# t/mail/poll-cursor.test — the inbox poll cursor lives in the LOG, not in the
# poller goroutine (offline-gap fix, decision-018). It is advanced only through
# record-poll-state, so full-log replay rebuilds it on restart and the poller
# resumes from where it left off: the next Email/changes hands back the mail that
# arrived while käsi was offline, instead of the goroutine re-anchoring the cursor
# to "now" and silently skipping the whole downtime window.
#
# This is the same crash-safety shape the pending outbox and the memory harvest
# already have — a durable value on the model, reconstructed by replay; only the
# JMAP Fetch effect runs live. It is also why the cursor is auditable: every step
# of the high-water mark is a message in the log, not a private variable.

send allow-sender   { address owner@example.test }
send set-reply-from { address kasi@decode.ee }

# No poll has run yet, so there is no high-water mark.
model email poll_cursor is ""

# The poll edge records each advance of the JMAP Email state as a log entry.
send record-poll-state { state jmap-state-A }
model email poll_cursor is jmap-state-A

# The process dies and comes back. The model is dropped and rebuilt from the log
# alone — and the cursor is still jmap-state-A, so the restarted poller calls
# Fetch(jmap-state-A) and Email/changes returns the offline window, rather than
# starting fresh from "now".
crash
restart
model email poll_cursor is jmap-state-A

# It advances monotonically as later polls record newer states — still logged,
# still auditable.
send record-poll-state { state jmap-state-B }
model email poll_cursor is jmap-state-B
